  "A pharmaceutical researcher is designing a new drug molecule and needs it to be water-soluble. She knows that polar molecules dissolve better in water. She is choosing between two candidate molecules: one with a tetrahedral shape (no lone pairs on the central atom, all identical substituents) and one with a trigonal pyramidal shape. Which candidate is more likely to be water-soluble?": "",
  "The trigonal pyramidal molecule, because its asymmetric shape creates a net dipole moment, making it polar": "",
  "Neither would be water-soluble because organic molecules are always nonpolar": "",
  "The tetrahedral molecule, because it has more bonds": "",
  "Both are equally water-soluble because they both have polar bonds": "",
  "A tetrahedral molecule with 4 identical groups is symmetric and nonpolar (dipoles cancel). A trigonal pyramidal molecule has a lone pair creating asymmetry, so its bond dipoles don't cancel, giving it a net dipole moment and polarity.": "",
  "An environmental chemist is studying why carbon dioxide (CO₂) is a greenhouse gas while nitrogen (N₂) is not. Both are atmospheric gases, but only CO₂ absorbs infrared radiation. She considers their molecular geometries. How does CO₂'s geometry allow it to absorb IR radiation during its asymmetric stretching mode?": "",
