  "CO₂ is always polar due to its double bonds": "",
  "CO₂ has a permanent dipole moment that absorbs IR radiation": "",
  "N₂ absorbs IR radiation equally but reflects it back to space": "",
  "Although CO₂ is linear and nonpolar at equilibrium, its asymmetric stretching and bending vibrations create temporary dipole changes that interact with infrared photons. N₂, being homonuclear and symmetric, cannot develop any dipole change.": "",
  "A chemical engineer is designing a refrigerant molecule to replace CFCs. She needs a molecule that has specific boiling point characteristics. She compares two molecules: CCl₄ (tetrahedral, symmetric) and CHCl₃ (tetrahedral but asymmetric). Why does CHCl₃ have a higher boiling point than CCl₄, despite CCl₄ being heavier?": "",
