  "CHCl₃ is polar (asymmetric substitution creates a net dipole), enabling dipole-dipole interactions that CCl₄ lacks due to its symmetry": "",
  "CCl₄ evaporates faster because it is heavier within the broader context of Chcl analysis": "",
  "CCl₄ is symmetric tetrahedral, so its bond dipoles cancel (nonpolar, only London dispersion forces). CHCl₃ has different substituents (H vs Cl), so dipoles don't cancel, making it polar with additional dipole-dipole interactions.": "",
